Now, as for the petitioner being denied access to the statements made to internal affairs. We don't have any laws covering this, so it becomes a constitutional question.
actxrz 2025-06-13 10:01 a.m.
yes, i agree. it does become a constitutional question which is why i go into arguing testimonial and non-testimonial statements. it is only testimonial if:

1. it is made to law enforcement with the primary purpose of establishing or proving facts for a criminal investigation or prosecution (it wasnt)
2. it was an affidavit, prior testimony, written statement to police, ying declaratings given in anticipation of use at trial, etc. (it wasnt)
3. it was made in a custodial interrogation (it wasnt)
actxrz 2025-06-13 10:01 a.m.
the statement given by the witness was non-testimonial and as i argue in the mtd, the claimant had no right to cross under the Sixth Amendment Confrontation Clause
insertreality
lets compare it to a criminal trial
actxrz 2025-06-13 10:05 a.m.
your analogy to criminal trials (suggesting that the accuser is entitled to review and cross-examine all evidence before any administrative action) fails for 2 reasons

1. there is no constitutional right to discovery in administrative investigations. the Mathews balancing test governs, not Brady v. Maryland
actxrz 2025-06-13 10:06 a.m.
the test is:

- the private interest affected
- the risk of erroneous deprivation through the procedures set in place, and
- the government's interest in maintain effiennt operations of the dept. and confidentiality
actxrz 2025-06-13 10:10 a.m.
2. due process is minimal an dept. administrative hearings

[t]he fundamental requirement of due process is the opportunity to be heard at a meaningful time and in a meaningful manner. Mathews v. Eldridge, 424 U.S. 319, 333 (1976); quoting Armstrong v. Manzo, 380 U.S. 545, 552, 85 S. Ct. 1187, 14 L. Ed. 2d 62 (1965).

[a]n essential principle of due process is that a deprivation of life, liberty, or property be preceded by notice and opportunity for hearing appropriate to the nature of the case. Cleveland Board of Education v. Loudermill, 470 U.S. at 532, 542 (1985).
actxrz 2025-06-13 10:12 a.m.
so it may seem that it is "unfair" to deny access to IA statements during investigation, but the constitutional standard is not fairness in the abstract but whether the process was fundamentally adequate. as long as the accused:

(1) received a notice of the accusations against him,
(2) was allowed to respond prior to discliplinary action, and
(3) is now afforded full confrontation at hearing.

the due process is satisfied.
actxrz 2025-06-13 10:13 a.m.
now what does "full confrontation" mean?
actxrz 2025-06-13 10:13 a.m.
the ability to cross-examine witnesses and view the evidence
